The community similarity-to-forest index was significantly correlated with tree cover within a 120 m radius of each sampling point (t = 10.61; 
      
       p
      <0.001; 
      
       Fig. 4
      ). We found no relationship between native ichneumonid abundance and tree cover (z = 1.33; 
      
       p = 
      0.183). Despite a lack of statistical significance, we observed three general patterns (
      
       Fig. 4
      ): (1) when surrounding tree cover within 120 m was higher than 90%, native ichneumonids were present about 90% of the time; (2) native ichneumonids were encountered about 60% of the time when surrounding tree cover was between 38 and 90%; and (3) native ichneumonids were not found when surrounding tree cover was less than 38%.
